{{DISPLAYTITLE:<span style="display:block;text-align:center;font-size:300%;font-style:italic;line-height:1em;">Remembering the Templars</span>}}
<center>[[File:Knights Templar - geograph.org.uk - 911186.jpg|600x320px|Knights Templar Poor Fellow-Soldiers of Christ and of the Temple of Solomon, two soldiers on one horse, the early symbol of the Knights Templar's poverty and dedication to Christ. Statue on a column in Church Court, Inner Temple in UK.]]</center>{{clear}}
== Introduction ==
The '''Poor Fellow-Soldiers of Christ and of the Temple of Solomon''', commonly known as the '''[[Remembering the Templars/Templars|Knights Templar]]''', the '''Order of the Temple''' or simply as '''Templars''', were among the most famous of the [[Biblical Studies/Christianity/Roman Catholicism|Roman Catholic Church]] [[Remembering_the_Templars#Military_orders|military order]]s. Founded during the [[Remembering the Templars/Age|High Middle Ages]] after the [[w:First Crusade|First Crusade]] to help protect Christian pilgrims, the organization lasted for nearly two centuries.

Officially endorsed by Roman Catholic Church around 1129, the Order became a favored charity throughout Christendom, and grew rapidly in membership and power. Templar knights, in their distinctive white [[w:Mantle (vesture)|mantles]] with a red [[w:Christian cross|cross]], were among the most skilled fighting units of the [[w:Crusades|Crusades]]. Non-combatant members of the Order managed a large economic infrastructure throughout [[w:Christendom|Christendom]], innovating financial techniques that were an early form of [[w:banking|banking]], and building [[w:fortification|fortification]]s across Europe and the [[w:Holy Land|Holy Land]].

The Templars' existence was tied closely to the Crusades; when the Holy Land was lost, support for the Order faded. Rumors about the Templars' secret initiation ceremony created mistrust, and King [[w:Philip IV of France|Philip IV of France]] (Philippe le Bel), deeply in debt to the Order, took advantage of the situation. In 1307, many of the Order's members in France were charges of heresy, arrested, tortured into giving [[w:false confession|false confession]]s, and then [[w:death by burning|burned at the stake]]. Under pressure from King Philip, [[w:Pope Clement V|Pope Clement V]] disbanded the Order in 1312. The abrupt disappearance of a major part of the European infrastructure gave rise to speculation and legends, which have kept the "Templar" name alive into the modern day. Only recently did we learn that in [[w:1314|1314]] the Order had secretly been pardoned by [[w:Pope Clement V|Pope Clement V]].

{{:Remembering the Templars/Age}}

== The Crusades and the Reconquista ==
[[w:Crusades|The Crusades]] was one of the most important events of the period, consisting in a series of religious Crusades, in which [[w:Christian|Christian]]s fought to retake Palestine from the [[w:Seljuk Turks|Seljuk Turks]]. The Crusades impacted all levels of society in the High Middle Ages, from the kings and emperors who themselves led the Crusades, to the lowest peasants whose lords were often absent in the east. The height of the Crusades was the 12th century, following the First Crusade and the foundation of the [[w:Crusader state|Crusader state]]s; in the 13th century and beyond, Crusades were also directed against fellow Christians, and in eastern and northern Europe, non-Muslim pagans. Expanded contact with the east, especially among the city-states of Italy, would eventually help spark the Italian [[w:Renaissance|Renaissance]], that then spread throughout the whole of western [[w:Christendom|Christendom]]. The [[History of Western Theatre: 17th_Century to Now/Late German 18th#.22Nathan the Wise.22|late German 18th century theater play "Nathan the Wise" that unfolds in the 12th century Jerusalem]] can be interesting to better contextualize the epoch.

